**The Most Important Distinction --- Input Validation vs Output
Encoding**

+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| **Input Validation**              | **Output Encoding**               |
|                                   |                                   |
| -   **Happens at:** when data     | -   **Happens at:** when data     |
|     enters the application        |     leaves the application and    |
|                                   |     enters an output context      |
| -   **Purpose:** reject data that |     (HTML, JS, URL, CSS)          |
|     should never exist (SQL       |                                   |
|     keywords in a postcode,       | -   **Purpose:** ensure the       |
|     script tags in a number       |     browser\'s parser treats user |
|     field)                        |     data as inert text, never as  |
|                                   |     executable code structure     |
| -   **Limitation:** you cannot    |                                   |
|     safely filter all XSS         | -   **Strength:** works on any    |
|     characters from free-text     |     input, including legitimate   |
|     fields (names, addresses,     |     apostrophes, angle brackets,  |
|     comments) without breaking    |     and special characters        |
|     legitimate input              |                                   |
|                                   | -   **Verdict:** the actual XSS   |
| -   **Verdict:** necessary but    |     fix --- encoding cannot be    |
|     not sufficient as an XSS      |     bypassed the way filters can  |
|     control                       |                                   |
+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Layer your defences:** validate at input (allowlist where possible)
  **+** encode at output (context-appropriate) **+** set HttpOnly &
  Secure cookie flags **+** deploy a strict Content Security Policy. **No
  single mitigation is sufficient alone.** Each layer limits the impact
  when --- not if --- another layer has a gap.

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
